  "opinion": "As a 19-year-old mechanic living in Milan, I've found that talking about healthcare and COVID vaccines can be tricky, especially with my anxious nature and being an immigrant trying to fit in. I work part-time, so I'm around different people at the garage and in the city, and my high extraversion means I enjoy chatting, but my moderate neuroticism makes me worry about saying the wrong thing. I remember one time at work, a colleague started debating vaccines loudly, and I felt my heart race—I just wanted to avoid conflict. My approach is to listen first, maybe share a bit from my own experience, like how getting vaccinated helped me feel safer when visiting family back home, which ties into my Christian beliefs about caring for others. I don't spend much time on social media, just a few times a month, so I rely more on conversations in person or what I hear from trusted sources, like my boss or local health clinics. In Milan, there's a mix of opinions, and as someone with moderate openness, I try to stay curious without pushing too hard. I think it's key to be respectful, especially since my parents had different educations—one with no formal schooling and one with a master's—so I've learned to value diverse perspectives. When discussions get heated, I might steer the talk toward my hobbies, like birdwatching or gardening, to lighten the mood. Overall, I believe in being honest but gentle, focusing on shared goals like community health, and not letting my anxiety shut me down. It's about balancing my extraverted side with my need for peace, and remembering that as a young, single man without kids, I have a role in keeping others safe too.",
